1. Background¶

Neutrino detection: importance and methods

Related experiment: DUNE, neutrino oscillations, LAr chamber

Pixel detector technology to overcome challenges in detecting particle in large scale (kilotons) detector Previous version: Analog Q-pix, 16-channel bullseye, Argon gas chamber --> prototype for electronics test

This version: ASIC circuits, LAr, smaller scale of more realistic usage

  • Impurities in Ar like Oxygen, Water leaking in from outside the chamber can make lifetime measurement inaccurate. When we did with analog Q-pix, we used PyBoltz to calculate the affect the impurities at different concentration has to the electron diffusion (the distribution of electrons cloud corelates to how much impurities are attached to the drifting electrons).

  • For most efficient test, we want Liquid Argon to be pure all the time. Thus, we construct a purifier which filters out Oxygen and Water during regeneration process and provides us with pure liquid argon to refill the TPC.

  • This experiment involves constructing the purity monitor (field cage) and a purifier (nipple with copper catalysts and molecular sieves) to experiment with the process. The main goal this summer is to get the system working and measure the purity of the output determined by electron lifetime measurement.

  • Once the Q-Pix ASICs arrive, we can install it into the chamber with liquid argon and collect data.

2. Purity Monitor¶

Impurities in liquid Argon can ionize and lead to electrical discharge between the cathode and anode. The measurement of these discharges indicates the impurity level.

The purity monitor consists of a field cage generating uniform electric field. Electrons are generated at the cathode of the field cage via the photoelectric effect. A series of ultraviolet light pulses from xenon flash lamp is transmitted through a fiber optic cable to the photo-cathode positioned at the center of the field cage, stripping electrons from the material (we use a gold-coated plate). These electrons then drift upward through liquid Argon from cathode and are collected at anode. Wire meshes are placed on both ends of field cage to shield the cathode and anode from induced current.

2.1 Pressure Gauges:¶

We use rough and turbo pumps to put the system into vacuum and use pressure gauges to monitor the pressure drop as time preceeds. We use Convectron Gauge (CG) and Ion Gauge (IG).

CG works under high pressure down to 5e-2 Torr and IG only works from pressure less than 5e-2 Torr. As the pump the system down, we switch from CG to IG for an accurate low pressure readings.

IG can be damaged under high pressure, it is crucial to have the system switch the IG off when the pressure exceeds its 5e-2 Torr limit.

There are 2 ways to do this: 1) Device's built-in logic: Connect pin1,2 (GND) of the pressure gauge together, IG will be auto-on-off based on CG pressure. Switch to display summary to show both CG, IG. This way is safer as we have display and independent of the PC status.

2) Python control through serial communcation: The Hornet (pressure gauges) connection to RS485, TXD A+ (red pin9 (B+)), TXD B- (purple pin6 (A-)). Use the code Here to send command and read result in ASCII. Use the value to decide if IG should be on/off.

def get_slope(x, y):
    coefficients = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)
    slope = coefficients[0]
    intercept = coefficients[1]
    return slope, intercept

CQin = (1)*(CVin*1e-3) #C=1pF
AQin = (1)*(AVin*1e-3)

2.5 Electron lifetime calculation¶

20240612

Impurities in the medium attaches to the drifting electron, causing $Q_A$, the charge measured at anode to be smaller than $Q_C$ at cathode. The ratio $Q_A/Q_C$ is used to calculate electron lifetime.

Drift electron attenuation in a purity monitor as a function of electron lifetime: $\tau = -\frac{t_{\text{drift}}}{\ln(Q_A / Q_C)}$

using the calibration to convert voltage (mV) to charge (pC),

$Q_Cin=0.61V_Cout + 11.93$

$Q_Ain=0.64V_Aout + 4.70$

%matplotlib inline

def get_data(file_path):
    plt.rcParams['font.size'] = 16
    df = pd.read_csv(file_path,skiprows=14)
    time = np.array(df["TIME"])
    CH2 = np.array(df["CH2"])
    CH3 = np.array(df["CH3"])    
    return time,CH2,CH3

def calc(CV1,CV2,AV1,AV2,t1,t2,t3,t4):
    delt = t3-t1
    VC = np.abs(CV2-CV1)
    VA = np.abs(AV2-AV1)
    #convert to Q with linear fit from calibration 
    QC = round(VC*0.00061+0.01193,5)
    QA = round(VA*0.00064+0.00470,5)
    ratio = round(QC/QA,2)
    tau = round(delt/(np.log(ratio)),1)
    n = 1/((4e12)*(tau*1e-6))
    print(f"tdrift = {round(delt,1)} μs, QA = {QA} pC, QC = {QC} pC, QC/QA = {ratio}, 𝜏 = {tau} μs, n = {round(n*1e9,2)} ppb")

3. Purifier & LAr Regeneration¶

Two main impurities in the LAr chamber are water and oxygen. High-purity liquid argon can be produced during cryogenic separation of air. We input liquid argon into the purifier which heats it up as it flows through the filters, this effectively separates the components by their boiling points, leaving pure argon at the output.

3.1 Regeneration process & Setup¶

Liquid Argon Input $\rightarrow$ 0.3 kg molecular sieves in the bottom nipple for water removal $\rightarrow$ 1.3 kg copper catalysts (GetterMax 133 tablets) in the upper nipple for oxygen removal $\rightarrow$ Pure Liquid Argon Output

In the regeneration process of liquid argon, molecular sieves absorb smaller molecules (water, other impurities) into its pores while allowing larger molecules (liquid argon) to pass through. while copper catalysts are used to reduce oxygen. The copper oxide in the catalyst reacts with hydrogen to form solid copper and water vapor, effectively removing oxygen from the system. This process ensures the high purity of regenerated liquid argon for our use in electronic testing of Q-pix pixel detector.

$CuO+H_2 \rightarrow Cu+H_2O$

We use a copper based catalyst, GetterMax133 tablets which are activated during the regeneration process for oxygen reduction. This requires a gas mixture of 1-2% $H_2$. Hydrogen gas acts as a reducing agent and removes $O_2$. The copper oxide heats up and reacts with the hydrogen molecules, producing solid copper metal and water vapor.

def get_datafromdat(filename):
    with open(filename, 'r') as f:
        Timestamp, Hours, AIN0, AIN2, AIN4 = [],[],[],[],[]
        for line in f:
            columns = line.split()
            unixtime = columns[0]
            Timestamp.append(columns[0])
            
            Hours.append(datetime.datetime.fromtimestamp(float(unixtime)).strftime('%H:%M'))
            """
            formattime = datetime.datetime.fromtimestamp(float(unixtime))
            time_str = formattime.strftime('%H:%M:%S')
            Hours.append(time_str)
            """
            AIN0.append(round(float(columns[1]),2))
            AIN2.append(round(float(columns[3]),2))
            AIN4.append(round(float(columns[5]),2))
    return Timestamp, Hours, AIN0, AIN2, AIN4
    
def plot_T7data(filename, labels=False):
    filepath = "TempRead/"+filename
    plt.rcParams['font.size'] = 16
    Timestamp, Hours, AIN0, AIN2, AIN4 = get_datafromdat(filepath)
    colors = ["black","orange","green"]
    
    evr = 100
    if labels:
        plt.plot(Hours[::evr],AIN0[::evr], label = "AIN0", color = colors[0])
        plt.plot(Hours[::evr],AIN2[::evr], label = "AIN2", color = colors[1])
        plt.plot(Hours[::evr],AIN4[::evr], label = "AIN4", color = colors[2])
    else:
        plt.plot(Hours[::evr],AIN0[::evr], color = colors[0])
        plt.plot(Hours[::evr],AIN2[::evr], color = colors[1])
        plt.plot(Hours[::evr],AIN4[::evr], color = colors[2])

GUI design for Temperature display¶

20240613

LabJack T7 appends temperature readings to a .dat file simultaneously as the datalogger update temperature plot. Python code is used to grab latest data logged on the file and display on top of the experimental setup diagram to show temperature at different location thermocouples are installed. The display helps monitor the flow of gas/liquid inside the purifier during regeneration process and help us assess the heat loss at each state.

from IPython.display import clear_output

import matplotlib.image as mpimg

class MplCanvas(FigureCanvas):
    def __init__(self, parent=None, width=5, height=4, dpi=100):
        fig = Figure(figsize=(width, height), dpi=dpi)
        self.axes = fig.add_subplot(111)
        super(MplCanvas, self).__init__(fig)
        
        self.csv_file = 'Tempread/realtimedata_test2.csv'
        self.latest_entry = None 

        self.timer = QtCore.QTimer(self)
        self.timer.timeout.connect(self.update_image)
        self.timer.start(1000)  
    
    def latest_datacsv(self, csv_file):
        with open(csv_file, 'r') as file:
            data = csv.reader(file)
            for row in data:
                latest_entry = row
            return latest_entry
     
    def latest_datadat(self, dat_file):
        with open(dat_file, 'r') as file:
            lines = file.readlines()
            last_line = lines[-1].strip()
            latest_entry = last_line.split()
            return latest_entry
    
    def update_image(self):

        self.axes.cla() # Clear the canvas.
        
        #old code
        new_entry = self.latest_datacsv(self.csv_file)
        if new_entry and new_entry != self.latest_entry: 
            self.latest_entry = new_entry
            timestamp = str(new_entry[1])
            CH1 = round(float(new_entry[2]),2)
            CH2 = round(float(new_entry[3]),2)
            CH3 = round(float(new_entry[4]),2)
            CH4 = round(float(new_entry[5]),2)
            CH5 = round(float(new_entry[6]),2)
            CH6 = round(float(new_entry[7]),2)
            CH7 = round(float(new_entry[8]),2)

            #self.axes.scatter([1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7], [CH1, CH2, CH3, CH4, CH5, CH6, CH7]) #test
            
            #plot image 
            img = mpimg.imread('Tempread/Diagram.png')  
            self.axes.imshow(img)
            self.fontsize = 10
            #scatter plot on top of img 
            self.axes.text(430, 420, f"CH1: {CH1} °C", fontsize=self.fontsize, color='black', fontweight='bold')
            self.axes.scatter(390, 350, color='black', edgecolors='white')

            self.axes.text(450, 780, f"CH2: {CH2} °C", fontsize=self.fontsize, color='white', fontweight='bold')
            self.axes.scatter(500, 820, color='white', edgecolors='black')

            self.axes.text(470, 1170, f"CH3: {CH3} °C", fontsize=self.fontsize, color='red', fontweight='bold')

Serial Comm with Omega 8-channel¶

20240618

We want a temperature monitor device that provides both display and python communication. The Omega's 8 Channel Handheld Thermocouple Thermometer/Data Logger provides display with a software. The serial trace shows the hexadecimal written and read from the device. Through some decoding, we can extract the bits corresponding to the temperature read for thermocouple connected to each channel. This way we can have realtime display and data acquisation system for our GUI!

  • From serial trace in OM-HL-EH-TC, the serial communication shows

Write: 01 16 7B 28 48 4C 45 48 54 43 34 30 39 35 67 71 29 7D 7E 04

Read: 01 16 7b 28 48 4c 45 48 54 43 34 30 39 35 68 71 e3 00 2b 01 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 c6 29 7d 7e 04

where the first 16 bits and last 4 bits are the same in all T readings. And we suspect that the middle 16 bits represents temperature readings for the 8 channels (2 bits or 4 digits per channel).

  • Temperature is recorded in 4 digits Hexadecimal number read backward (Little endian system: stores the least-significant byte at the smallest address) For example, the conversion between the reading in channel T2 would be, 2b 01 --> 012b --> 299 --> 29.9 degrees Celsius
In [1]:
print("T1: ", int("00e3",16))
print("T2: ", int("012b",16))

T1:  227
T2:  299
  • To ensure this logic makes sense, double check with the device's spec where

T range = -200～1800℃ --> report in -2000-180000 *10℃

18000 = 4650

--> 2 hex bits are enough to display the whole range of temp

def readtemp(ser, byte_data):
    ser.write(byte_data)
    print(f"Write: {byte_data.hex()}")     
    time.sleep(0.1) 
    print(ser.in_waiting)
    if ser.in_waiting == 37:
        response = ser.readline()
        if response:
            response_hex = response.hex()        
            print(f"Read:  {response_hex}")

            T1 = int(response_hex[34:36] + response_hex[32:34], 16) / 10  # T1                                 
            T2 = int(response_hex[38:40] + response_hex[36:38], 16) / 10  # T2

            T4 = int(response_hex[46:48] + response_hex[44:46], 16) / 10  # T4
            
            T5 = int(response_hex[50:52] + response_hex[48:50], 16) / 10  # T5                                 
            T6 = int(response_hex[54:56] + response_hex[52:54], 16) / 10  # T6                                 
            T7 = int(response_hex[58:60] + response_hex[56:58], 16) / 10  # T7                                
            T8 = int(response_hex[62:64] + response_hex[60:62], 16) / 10  # T8
    
            print(f"T1: {T1}, T2: {T2}, T3: {T3}, T4: {T4}\nT5: {T5}, T6: {T6}, T7: {T7}, T8: {T8}\n")

    try:
        now = dt.now()
        nowstr = now.strftime('%Y%m%dT%H%M%S')
        print(nowstr)
        readtemp(ser, byte_data)

    except KeyboardInterrupt:

        ser.close()
        exit()
ser.close()

#Ver 2
import numpy as np
import serial
import time
from datetime import datetime as dt
import csv

def open_serial(serial_port):
    baud_rate = 38400
    ser = serial.Serial(serial_port, baud_rate, timeout=1)
    return ser
    
def hex_dec(T_hex):
    try:
        T_val = int(T_hex, 16)
        T_max = 18000  # 1800C max
        hex_max = 0xFFFF  # FFFF max 
        if T_val > T_max: 
            T = -(hex_max - T_val + 1) / 10 ##negative value
        else:
            T = T_val / 10
        return T
    except ValueError:
        return 'err'

def parse_temp(response):
    response_hex = response.hex()
    temperatures = []

    for i in range(8):
        hex_str = response_hex[34 + i*4:36 + i*4] + response_hex[32 + i*4:34 + i*4]
        temperatures.append(hex_dec(hex_str))

    return tuple(temperatures)

def readtemp(ser, byte_data):
    ser.write(byte_data)

    response = ser.readline()
    while True:
        ser.write(byte_data)
        time.sleep(0.1) 
        if ser.in_waiting == 37:
            response = ser.readline()
            if response:
                try:
                    return parse_temp(response)
                except ValueError:
                    return ('err',) * 8 #if not valid hex, put err
            else:
                return (np.nan,) * 8 #if no response, put nan
    
#read temp
ser = open_serial('/dev/cu.usbserial-110') 
hex_data = [0x01, 0x16, 0x7B, 0x28, 0x48, 0x4C, 0x45, 0x48, 0x54, 0x43, 0x34, 0x30, 0x39, 0x35, 0x67, 0x71, 0x29, 0x7D, 0x7E, 0x04]
byte_data = bytearray(hex_data)

now = dt.now()
filename = "temp_log_"+str(now.strftime('%Y%m%d%H%M'))+".csv"
print("starting temperature log file: "+filename)

with open(filename, 'a') as csvfile:
    csvwriter = csv.writer(csvfile)
    csvwriter.writerow(['DateTimestamp','T1','T2','T3','T4','T5','T6','T7','T8'])

    while True:
        now = dt.now()
        nowstr = now.strftime('%Y%m%dT%H%M%S')
        T1,T2,T3,T4,T5,T6,T7,T8 = readtemp(ser, byte_data) 
        print(f"{nowstr},{T1},{T2},{T3},{T4},{T5},{T6},{T7},{T8}")
        csvwriter.writerow([nowstr,T1,T2,T3,T4,T5,T6,T7,T8])
        csvfile.flush()
    csvfile.close()     
    ser.close()

import os

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

import matplotlib.dates as mdates
from datetime import datetime as dt

def plotTemp(filepath):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,4), dpi = 100)
    colors = [(183, 101, 224), (93, 131, 212), (49, 205, 222), (36, 214, 75), (214, 125, 36), (230, 78, 192), (209, 84, 65), (0, 184, 235)]
    df = pd.read_csv(filepath)
    df['Time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Time'], format='%Y%m%dT%H%M%S.%f')
    time = df['Time']
    for i in range(8):
        plt.plot(np.array(time), np.array(df[f"T{i+1}"]),color = [colors[i][0]/235,colors[i][1]/235,colors[i][2]/235], label = f"T{i+1}")
    
    plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%H:%M:%S'))
    #plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.HourLocator(interval=1))
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel('Time')
    plt.ylabel('Temperature (°C)')
    plt.ylim(0,25)
    plt.title(filepath[60:-11])
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    
def plotHum(filepath):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,4), dpi = 100)
    df = pd.read_csv(filepath)
    df['Time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Time'], format='%Y%m%dT%H%M%S.%f')
    time = df['Time']
    plt.plot(np.array(time), np.array(df["HUM"]),color = 'red', label = "HUM")
    plt.plot(np.array(time), np.array(df["TMP"]),color = 'blue', label = "TMP")
    plt.plot(np.array(time), np.array(df["DEW"]),color = 'black', label = "DEW")
    
    plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%H:%M:%S'))
    #plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.HourLocator(interval=1))
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel('Time')
    plt.ylabel('Relative Humidity (%)')
    plt.title(filepath[60:-11])
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
def plotComp(tempfile, humfile):
    df_temp = pd.read_csv(tempfile)
    df_hum = pd.read_csv(humfile)
    
    t1 = np.array(pd.to_datetime(df_temp['Time'], format='%Y%m%dT%H%M%S.%f'))
    t2 = np.array(pd.to_datetime(df_hum['Time'], format='%Y%m%dT%H%M%S.%f'))
    data1 = np.array(df_temp['T8'])
    data2 = np.array(df_hum["HUM"])
    
    fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,4), dpi = 100)
    color1 = 'tab:blue'
    ax1.set_xlabel('Time')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Output Temperature (°C)', color=color1)
    ax1.plot(t1, data1, color=color1)
    ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color1)
    ax1.set_ylim(15,30)
    
    ax1.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%H:%M:%S'))
    
    ax2 = ax1.twinx() 
    
    color2 = 'tab:red'
    ax2.set_ylabel('Relative Humdity (%)', color=color2)
    ax2.plot(t2, data2, color=color2)
    ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color2)
    
    ax2.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%H:%M:%S'))
    
    fig.tight_layout()  
    plt.show()

import csv

now_time = dt.datetime.now()
timestamp = str(now_time.strftime('%Y%m%dT%H%M%S.%f')[:-3])

filename = f"{timestamp}_templog.csv"
with open(filename, 'a') as csvfile:
    csvwriter = csv.writer(csvfile)
    csvwriter.writerow(['Timestamp','RTD1', 'RTD2','RTD3', 'RTD4', 'R1', 'R2','R3','R4','T1','T2','T3','T4'])
    ser = serial.Serial('COM4', 9600, timeout = 1)
    print(ser)
    while True:
        if ser.in_waiting:
            now_time = dt.datetime.now()
            timestamp = str(now_time.strftime('%Y%m%dT%H%M%S.%f')[:-3])
            line = str(ser.readline().decode('utf-8').strip())
            parts = line.split(',')
            RTD1 = parts[0]
            RTD2 = parts[1]
            RTD3 = parts[2]
            RTD4 = parts[3]

            R1 = parts[4]
            R2 = parts[5]
            R3 = parts[6]
            R4 = parts[7]

            T1 = parts[8]
            T2 = parts[9]
            T3 = parts[10]
            T4 = parts[11]

            csvwriter.writerow([timestamp, RTD1, RTD2, RTD3, RTD4, R1, R2, R3, R4, T1, T2, T3, T4])
            print(f"{timestamp}\nRTDs: {RTD1}, {RTD2}, {RTD3}, {RTD4} \nResistants: {R1}, {R2}, {R3}, {R4}\nTemperatures:\nT1 = {T1}\nT2 = {T2}\nT3 = {T3}\nT4 = {T4} \n")

        csvfile.flush()

def plotAbsHum(filepath):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,4), dpi = 100)
    df = pd.read_csv(filepath)
    df['Time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Time'], format='%Y%m%dT%H%M%S.%f')
    time = df['Time']
    T = df['TMP']
    rh = df["HUM"]
    df['absHUM'] = (6.112*np.exp((17.67*T)/(T+243.5))*rh*2.1674)/(273.15+T)
    plt.plot(np.array(time), np.array(df["absHUM"]),color = 'red')
    
    plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%H:%M:%S'))
    plt.xlabel('Time')
    plt.ylabel(f'Absolute Humidity (g/$m^3$)')
    plt.title("Absolute Humidity")
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,4), dpi = 100)
    plt.plot(np.array(time), np.array(df["HUM"]),color = 'magenta')
    plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%H:%M:%S'))
    plt.xlabel('Time')
    plt.ylabel(f'Absolute Humidity (g/$m^3$)')
    plt.title("Relative Humidity and Temperature")

import matplotlib.ticker as ticker 
def plotCompAbs(merged_df):
    data1 = np.array(merged_df["\tT8 PurOUT-oC"])
    data2 = np.array(merged_df["absHUM"])
    merged_df['datetime'] = pd.to_datetime(merged_df["TIME"], format='%H:%M:%S')
    
    t = np.array(merged_df["datetime"])
    print()
    
    fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,4), dpi = 200)
    color1 = 'tab:blue'
    ax1.set_xlabel('Time')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Output Temperature (°C)', color=color1)
    ax1.plot(t, data1, color=color1)
    ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color1)
    ax1.set_ylim(0,250)
    
    ax1.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%H:%M:%S'))
    
    ax2 = ax1.twinx() 
    
    color2 = 'tab:red'
    ax2.set_ylabel(f'Absolute Humdity (g/$m^3$ = ppm)', color=color2)
    ax2.plot(t, data2, color=color2)
    
    #ax2.set_ylim(6.8,7.5)
    ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color2)
    ax2.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%H:%M:%S'))
 
    fig.tight_layout() 
    plt.title("20240628 regen test2")
    ax1.yaxis.grid() 
    ax1.xaxis.grid()
    plt.show()

#for new data format 

def plotCompAbs(tempfile, humfile):
    df_temp = pd.read_csv(tempfile)
    df_hum = pd.read_csv(humfile)
    
    t1 = np.array(pd.to_datetime(df_temp['Time'], format='%Y%m%dT%H%M%S.%f'))
    t2 = np.array(pd.to_datetime(df_hum['Time'], format='%Y%m%dT%H%M%S.%f'))
    data1 = np.array(df_temp['T8'])
    
    
    #use the humidity sensor's temperature readings to calculate absolute humidity
    T = df_hum['TMP']
    rh = df_hum['HUM']
    df_hum['absHUM'] = (6.112*np.exp((17.67*T)/(T+243.5))*rh*2.1674)/(273.15+T)

    data2 = np.array(df_hum["absHUM"])

    
    fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,4), dpi = 100)
    color1 = 'tab:blue'
    ax1.set_xlabel('Time')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Output Temperature (°C)', color=color1)
    ax1.plot(t1, data1, color=color1)
    ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color1)
    ax1.set_ylim(20,23)
    
    ax1.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%H:%M:%S'))
    
    ax2 = ax1.twinx() 
    
    color2 = 'tab:red'
    ax2.set_ylabel('Absolute Humdity (%)', color=color2)
    ax2.plot(t2,data2 , color=color2)
    
    ax2.set_ylim(7,7.5)
    ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color2)
    ax2.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%H:%M:%S'))

    
    fig.tight_layout()  
    plt.show()
